				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{CE}} = C_{\text{P}} /C_{\text{T}} \times 100\% ,$$\end{document} where CT is the total Coulomb consumption calculated by integrating the area under the current–time curve (i–t curve). CP is the Coulomb in the product, and its calculation formula is CP = b × n×F, where b is the number of electrons in the product (8 eq mol−1), n is the number of moles of the product, and F is Faraday constant (96,485 C mol−1). The volumetric acetate production rate = acetate concentration/number of days of reaction. The highest volumetric acetate production rate was obtained by intercomparison.
